@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@prev "Copyright"
@next "Requirements"

                              @{b}Introduction@{ub}
                          ====================

Tape Editor is intended to be used in conjunction with Mouse Control. There
isn't really any other use for it than to edit tape files for Mouse Control.
It provides a user-friendly (I hope) environment for easy creation and
debugging of tapes.

Tape Editor was written in Blitz Basic 2.1

                                                 Roger Light

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Introduction"

                             @{b}Requirements@{ub}
                         ====================

    Mouse Control v1.3. This should be in this archive, but if it isn't,
    then you can download the latest version from the Aminet at
    utils/wb/mouse_control.lha
    @{B}Mouse Control v1.2 is not compatible with this version of Tape Editor!@{ub}

    To run Tape Editor, you need WB 3.0 absolute minimum. This is due to
    some of the gadget functions so there is no way I'm ever going to
    support any less than 3.0. Also, XEN font is recommened, but if not
    found, then topaz will be used. I used to like topaz, then tried XEN for
    a while. Trust me, it's lots nicer.

    To use the playback feature, ARexx must be running as well as Mouse
    Control.


@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "ARexx"
@prev "Requirements"

                                 @{b}Usage@{ub}
                             =============

There are only a few buttons to press, so this shouldn't be too difficult.

Buttons:-

      o Play - Used to send the current tape to Mouse Control for playback.
          Disabled if Mouse Control isn't running. (Can be enabled by
          runnning Mouse Control)

      o New - Creates a new tape with the same parameters as are currently
         stored, but will all commands reset to NOPE

      o Add - Adds a new command NOPE at the bottom of the list.

      o Insert - Inserts a new command NOPE into the tape above the
       currently selected command.

      o Delete - Deletes the currently selected command.

      o Up - Moves the currently selected command up the tape list.

      o Down - Moves the currently selected command down the tape list.

      o Load - Loads a tape file from disk.

      o Save - Saves the current tape file to disk.

Inputs:-

      o Commands - How many commands long the tape is to be (or is).
         Inputting a new value will cause a new tape to be created
         with all NOPEs

      o Distance - The initial value of distance for this tape (see
         mouse_control.guide) 

      o Increment - The initial value of increment for this tape (see
          mouse_control.guide)

      o Neg/Noneg - Initial condition of neg/noneg for this tape.

      o Cycle Gadget - Which command the currently selected cell is. Click
             to change (recommended you use Cycle to Menu or
             similar).

      o List View - The tape. This is the list of commands that will be
          executed by Mouse Control. First command is first in
          time. Click on command to edit it.

I think they're all fairly self explanatory, but if you get stuck then
contact me.

Keys:-

      o Esc - quits Tape Editor

      o Del/Backspace - Deletes current command

      o Space - toggles Neg/Noneg

      o Left/Right Cursor - Changes what the current command is

      o Up/Down Cursor - Moves up and down the tape.

      o "I" - Inserts a cell.

      o "A" - Adds a cell.

      o "D" - Deletes a cell.

      o "N" - Creates a new tape.

      o "P" - Plays the current tape (if possible)

      o "L" - Loads a tape from disk.

      o "S" - Saves the current tape to disk.

      o  Tab/Shift Tab - Cycles through Commands/Distance/Increment.

@endnode

@node "ARexx" "ARexx"
@next "Technical"
@prev "Usage"

                            @{b}ARexx Interface@{ub}
                        =======================

Tape Editor opens an ARexx port TAPE_EDITOR to communicate with Mouse
Control.

Currently, it supports one command that is of no interest to the user, but
should be documented I feel. This command is "MOUSE_CONTROL". Basically,
when Tape Editor starts, it looks for Mouse Control's ARexx port and if it
isn't there - disables the "Play" button. So when Mouse Control is run, it
sends Tape Editor a message saying that it is, so Tape Editor enables the
"Play" button. You can't try and fool Tape Editor into thinking that Mouse
Control is there by sending the command yourself because it looks for Mouse
Control's ARexx port as well when it receives the command.

@endnode

